<TITLE> Sri Lankan TV staff release minister held hostage </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 COLOMBO, Dec 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Staff at Sri Lanka's state television broadcaster on Thursday released a minister they had taken hostage after his aide manhandled their director, company officials said. Non-cabinet labour minister Mervyn Silva was released after he apologised for the incident. Silva entered the premises of state-owned Rupavahini earlier on Thursday complaining that his speech at a ceremony the previous day to reopen a bridge destroyed by the 2004 tsunami was not aired. His aide then dragged the news director out of the newsroom, tearing open his shirt. The broadcaster's irate staff then hemmed the minister and his entourage into a small room, and would not let them leave, demanding an apology. "If my action is considered as a wrong act, I would like to apologise to the employees," Silva said. A Reuters reporter at the scene said police armed with teargas were standing at the ready, and that some members of staff manhandled the minister -- who has been involved in past brawls with the media -- as he was later escorted out of the premises. Media Minister Anura Priyadharshana Yapa called the incident "unfortunat
